      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":2,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":4,\"target_duration_minutes\":30,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":450,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":450,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start with a brisk 5-minute walk to ease into movement. Let your breathing settle before you begin running.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":450,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Run at a comfortable, conversational pace. You should be able to speak in full sentences. This is aerobic base building — resist the urge to push harder.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Slow to an easy walk for the final 5 minutes. Let your heart rate come down naturally.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Begin with 5 minutes of easy walking before you start running. A few gentle leg swings and ankle circles are a nice addition if you have time.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk for 5 minutes after your run, then spend 5–10 minutes on light static stretching — calves, quads, and hips are the priority.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This is your foundational aerobic run for the week. At 15 km per week with a 5 km long run, your aerobic base is still developing, and most of your running should feel genuinely easy. The 7:00–8:00 /km range is your sweet spot — comfortable enough that you could hold a conversation. The physiological goal here is to stimulate mitochondrial density and improve fat oxidation, which forms the engine of your 5K fitness. Keep it easy today so you arrive at the weekend feeling fresh for your long run.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Run with Strides\",\"target_distance_km\":4,\"target_duration_minutes\":32,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":450,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":390,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start with a 5-minute easy walk to warm your muscles and joints before running begins.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":18,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":450,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Run at your comfortable easy pace — conversational effort. This is the main aerobic block of the session.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":4,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":390,\"intensity\":\"Moderate\",\"repetitions\":4,\"notes\":\"Four short 20-second strides at a comfortably brisk pace — not a sprint, more like a smooth, controlled pickup. Walk or jog easy for 60 seconds between each one. These teach your legs to move a little faster without taxing your aerobic system.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy walk to close out the session and bring your heart rate back to baseline.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Five minutes of easy walking followed by the first portion of your easy run. Let your body warm up gradually before the strides at the end.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk for 5 minutes. Focus on slow, deep breathing. Add gentle hip flexor and calf stretches if your legs feel tight.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This run introduces short strides at the end — a low-risk, high-reward tool for beginners. Strides are brief accelerations (about 20 seconds) that gently introduce your neuromuscular system to faster movement patterns without creating meaningful fatigue. Think of them as waking your legs up, not racing. Over the coming weeks, this neuromuscular conditioning will directly support your ability to run the Parkrun 5K at a stronger, more efficient pace. Keep the effort controlled — these should feel fun and smooth, not hard.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Long Easy Run\",\"target_distance_km\":6,\"target_duration_minutes\":45,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":465,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":465,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Begin with a 5-minute brisk walk. Ease into your running pace gradually — the first kilometre should feel almost effortlessly slow.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":35,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":465,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Run at a steady, comfortable easy pace throughout. Your breathing should be relaxed and controlled. If you feel like you need to slow down, slow down — the goal is time on feet, not pace.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Transition to a walk for the final 5 minutes. Take this time to notice how your body feels after the longest effort of your week.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Start with a 5-minute walk, then ease gently into running. The first kilometre should feel almost too easy — that is correct. Your body needs time to settle into the aerobic groove.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk for at least 5 minutes after finishing. Prioritise stretching today — spend extra time on calves, hip flexors, and hamstrings. Hydrate well for the rest of the day.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Saturday is your long run day — the cornerstone of 5K training. Your current long run is 5 km, and this week we are nudging it up to 6 km, which stays well within the 10% weekly volume progression guideline. The long run builds aerobic capacity, strengthens connective tissue, and improves running economy over time — all of which contribute directly to your 5K goal. The pace should feel genuinely easy: 7:45–8:00 /km is perfectly appropriate here. Arriving at your long run already somewhat fatigued from earlier in the week is normal, so please do not chase your Tuesday or Thursday pace. Time on feet is the goal today.\",\"perceived_effort\":5}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
